{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653408"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:46:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:46:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18583"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18583"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76021"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11315"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61522"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10354"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26230"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76021"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe reticular formation is a complex network of neurons in the brainstem that plays a crucial role in consciousness and arousal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how the reticular formation processes sensory information?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Processes sensory information in discrete anatomical nuclei","Filters and integrates multiple sensory inputs simultaneously","Transmits all sensory information directly to consciousness","Processes each sensory modality independently","Responds only to intense sensory stimuli"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe reticular formation \u003Cstrong\u003Efilters and integrates multiple sensory inputs simultaneously\u003C/strong\u003E through its diffuse network of neurons. This allows for selective attention and determines which sensory information reaches conscious awareness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcesses sensory information in discrete anatomical nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E - The reticular formation consists of a diffuse network rather than discrete processing centres\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransmits all sensory information directly to consciousness\u003C/strong\u003E - The reticular formation selectively filters information rather than transmitting everything\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcesses each sensory modality independently\u003C/strong\u003E - Multiple sensory inputs are integrated together rather than processed separately\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResponds only to intense sensory stimuli\u003C/strong\u003E - The reticular formation processes both subtle and intense stimuli based on their relevance\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis filtering and integration function allows us to focus attention on relevant stimuli while maintaining awareness of our environment. The reticular formation receives collateral input from all major sensory pathways and can modulate which information reaches consciousness based on its significance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The reticular formation consists of a diffuse network of neurons extending from the medulla to the midbrain.","Reticular neurons receive collateral input from all major sensory pathways including visual, auditory, and somatosensory systems.","The reticular formation filters incoming sensory information to determine which stimuli reach conscious awareness."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61522"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18583"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61522"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T22:22:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T22:24:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11315"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76021"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ud